			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Before you try pulling a lvl 65 high risk....<a name="32795"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 4 04 6:20 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I would suggest that no one try pulling a high risk without at least half of the maximum defensive AA's (Fading Memories is also a MUST IMO) and gear of VT quality or better.
<br />
That said, a good way to practice the skills you will be using may be to try pulling entire LDoNs without the use of pacify.  Pacify is VERY ineffective in a level 65 high risk (not so bad at lower levels I understand).  What I generally do is as follows:
<br />
1. turn off attack, sneak up to get targets (and &lt;toggle last two targets hotbutton&gt<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-5.gif" border="0" alt="Wink" hspace="2" />
<br />
2.  use HoS on the closest mob - and run down the hall a bit to give me some room once the spellcast timer is going
<br />
3.  start casting mez on it - if it seems to be alone, I interrupt mez, by recasting it and running backwards before it lands, so I'm ready in case it had a friend or two lurking.  
<br />

<br />
Try to save your Fades for times that you absolutely must (more than 3 agroed at once is a good time for that).  But, if possible try to land a mez or a snare on one of the mobs before you fade - hopefully the others will reset, but the mezzed/snared one will stay away from them and not chain agro.  Sometimes I will use the same tactic as above except substitute snare for mez in steps 2 and 3, as this will give me time to react to possible adds (especially when i'm not sure, or there might be casters I didn't notice who aren't following, but are in the middle of trying to nuke me).
<br />
Speaking of casters, casters are your friend in High risk.  They would rather spend 4 seconds casting a 600 point nuke on you than hit you 4 times for 900 damage.  Kinda silly if you ask me, just mind that you dont' let them heal up or gate into a herd of their friends.  Pulling casters can be tricky, often, I will cast on them with HoS, break the line of sight, and keep them out of sight until I'm back with my group, hide around a corner, so that as soon as the caster sees me, and starts casting whatever it shall, the tank can take a few swings at it, and possibly even break its concentration.
<br />
BTW, I always leave 1 empty room between my group and the mobs I'm pulling - don't let them creep up on you, or your FM will be for naught, and all will die a horrible death.
<br />
These are some good habits which have worked for me, presented in as concise a fashion as I could - enjoy!</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
